e vacuum.\n    `y_f \u003d |\u003cŌą_f | Ōą_vac\u003e|`\n    Here, `Ōą_f` is the SU(2) spinor of the fermion (derived from its spreads), and `Ōą_vac` is the SU(2) spinor of the vacuum tuple `T_vac`.\n\n*   **The Mass Formula**: The mass of a fermion `f` is therefore given by its geometric coupling to the vacuum\u0027s geometric volume.\n    **`m_f ‚ąĚ |\u003cŌą_f | Ōą_vac\u003e| * V_vac`**\n\nThis is a profound statement: a particle has mass because its fundamental geometry \"resonates\" or \"aligns\" with the geometry of the vacuum. A particle whose geometry was perfectly \"orthogonal\" to the vacuum\u0027s geometry (`|\u003cŌą_f | Ōą_vac\u003e| \u003d 0`) would remain massless.\n\n### **4. The Geometric Origin of W and Z Boson Masses**\n\nThe same principle applies to the weak gauge bosons. Their masses arise from the interaction of their corresponding algebraic generators (the ladder and Cartan operators) with the vacuum state.\n\n*   **W Boson Mass**: The W boson is associated with the SU(2) ladder operators `T‚Āļ` and `T‚ĀĽ`. Its mass-squared is proportional to the \"action\" of these operators on the vacuum state.\n    `m_W¬≤ ‚ąĚ ||T‚Āļ Ōą_vac||¬≤ * V_vac¬≤`\n    This geometrically ties the W boson\u0027s mass to the SU(2) structure of the vacuum.\n\n*   **Z Boson Mass and the Weinberg Angle**: The Z boson corresponds to a mixture of the `T‚āÉ` and `Y` generators. Its mass arises similarly. Crucially, the mixing parameter‚ÄĒthe **Weinberg angle `őł_w`**‚ÄĒis no longer a free parameter but is predicted by the geometry of the vacuum spinor.\n    `sin¬≤őł_w \u003d s‚āā_vac \u003d |\u003c‚Üď|Ōą_vac\u003e|¬≤`\n    The Weinberg angle is simply the probability that the vacuum state, when measured, collapses into the \"down\" eigenstate.\n\n### **5. A Complete, Falsifiable Computational Program**\n\nThis geometric model of the Higgs mechanism is not just a story; it is a concrete, computationally verifiable and falsifiable theory.\n\n**The Ultimate Experiment**:\n1.  